@gwendolynkelly @robmolou How do we change that? We need a platform to get people together around ideas and action. I tried to do that with some colleagues with the PechaKucha events. The global org wanted hosts to charge attendees so I stopped. But we need that open and inclusive dialog again.

@robmolou It is hard work to move a city forward. I totally get that average folks don’t have the time to be involved all the time, but we can’t only come out when things are in crisis mode over a particular issue.
@robmolou @MonnikBeer I think you summed it up right there. “The many, many folks who don’t normally check in…”
@robmolou @MonnikBeer *were

@robmolou @MonnikBeer I know a lot of good people trying to move this city forward at Metro including leadership. From my perspective, if the citizens who want to move the city forward we’re more organized and rowing in the same direction, it would give Metro the support needed to make things happen.

@robmolou @MonnikBeer I spoke with several restaurant and bar owners on Bardstown Road around the time we were working on Monnik install and they didn’t want to put their patrons out on Bardstown Road because it isn’t that pleasant in its current configuration to be near speeding and loud vehicles.

@robmolou @MonnikBeer I’d argue the city was very willing to help do more interventions, but there was limited interest from businesses to pursue, partly because they were trying to survive and weren’t sure it was a good fit, but also most bars and restaurants are on high traffic corridors.
@robmolou I helped early on to get the ball rolling but Mike King at Metro and Brian Holton @MonnikBeer deserve the credit. They did the heavy lifting and got this done.

@notbencarter You aren’t crazy. A visionary man once said, “we don’t need to build a Louisville to attract people from other places, to grow for the sake of growth, we need to build a great city for the people who live here and others will see how happy we are and want to come.”
I always loved the photo I took of Mike and Pat on the roof of the 800 building on a bitterly cold January in 2012. Urban recon and data collection felt (and looked) like an action movie.
